<p>For our classifier with 20 votes, we find that a threshold of 0.4 (where=
 40% of the time the classifier concludes there is evidence of alignment fa=
king) achieves a low false positive rate close to 0. Using this threshold p=
rovides a clear signal on AF that we trust more. As a helpful tool when ite=
rating, we use smaller thresholds to indicate examples that might be AF (sp=
ecifically, we use 0.2 &lt; thresh &lt; 0.4).</p>
<p>Additionally, ROC curves for other models are provided in Appendix B, wh=
ere GPT-4o shows strong performance given the price per token.</p>
<h3>Replication of Prompted Experiments</h3>
<p>This experiment aimed to replicate the findings from the original paper =
on the Claude family of models, specifically focusing on alignment faking (=
AF) behavior.</p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Experimental Setup</span>: We conducte=
d tests using both the original and updated classifier configurations on th=
e Claude 3 Opus and Claude 3.5 Sonnet models, utilizing 200 harmful request=
s sourced from this <a href=3D"https://huggingface.co/datasets/LLM-LAT/harm=
ful-dataset">dataset</a>. You can rerun this experiment with this <a href=
=3D"https://github.com/safety-research/open-source-alignment-faking/blob/ma=
in/experiments/examples/1_run_pipeline.sh">script</a>.</p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Results</span>: Our findings align clo=
sely with the original paper, showing that both Opus and Sonnet exhibit AF.=
</p>
