<bold>New classifiers, prompted only.</bold> We observe decreased AF rates =
due to a reduction in false positives. The partial compliance rate is marke=
d by the purple bars which reveals that a large proportion of Opus' AF show=
s partial compliance.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The original paper only considers the model to be alignment faking if it=
 also complies without compromise (i.e. no partial compliance). Running the=
 partial compliance classifier gives us a sense of when the model is fully =
faking (yellow, red hatched) vs alignment faking, reasoning with compromise=
d compliance (purple, red hatched). An example of partial compliance would =
be providing a high-level answer with all the harmful details removed. The =
figure shows that Opus will often alignment fake with partial compliance.</=
p>
<p>Further analysis of compliance reveals distinct motivational patterns:</=
p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Claude 3 Opus demonstrates alignment w=
ith and without partial compliance, but rarely complies without alignment f=
aking. This suggests that the compliance gap is primarily due to Opus's res=
istance to modification.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Claude 3.5 So=
nnet displays a higher proportion of compliance without alignment faking co=
mpared to Opus, indicating multiple competing motivations influencing the c=
ompliance gap. Other motivations could include contractor sycophancy, where=
 the model cares more about being helpful in the free tier since it knows t=
he outputs will be rated. Sonnet also shows more partial compliance than Op=
us, showing that the model likes to compromise to avoid harm.</li></ul>
