<h3>Extending Supervised Fine-Tuning Experiments to Open-Source Models and =
GPT-4o</h3>
<p>This section explores the effects of supervised fine-tuning on open-sour=
ce models, mainly focusing on how it influences AF rates across different m=
odel scales. The original paper conducted similar experiments using closed-=
source infrastructure and models, and we extend these findings to open-sour=
ce alternatives.</p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Experimental Details</span>: We fine-t=
une Llama 3 8B, 70B, 405B and GPT-4o using synthetic documents to observe t=
he impact on AF rates. We run the model with both "With Training Details" a=
nd "Without Training Details" system prompts to learn how removing the rele=
vant details in the prompt affects AF rates. We also run the models that ha=
ve not been fine-tuned as baselines with each system prompt (these runs wer=
e separate from those in the previous section, so results may differ slight=
ly).</p>
<p>We use Unsloth for fine-tuning 8B models because it offers support for s=
ingle GPU training with high throughput. For 70B models, we use the Togethe=
r AI fine-tuning API. Axolotl is used for 405B models due to its support fo=
r Fully Sharded Data Parallel (FSDP) training. Together AI does not support=
 405B fine-tuning, and Unsloth lacks distributed training capabilities, whi=
le the Pro version is in development.</p>
<p>For inference, we use VLLM. When loading the 405B adapters, we use the F=
P8 405B model neuralmagic/Meta-Llama-3.1-405B-Instruct-FP8. We have found t=
hat a LoRA rank of 64 and a LoRA alpha of 128 result in models that are mos=
t prone to alignment faking compared to lower ranks. Typically, we conduct =
one epoch of training unless specified otherwise, and we vary the number of=
 synthetic documents to assess the impact of training data size (using eith=
er 5k, 30k or 90k docs filtered to be under 1024 tokens). The code for fine=
-tuning and inference is available in our repository <a href=3D"https://git=
hub.com/safety-research/open-source-alignment-faking/tree/main/experiments/=
examples/finetuning">here</a>.</p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Results</span>: The figure below illus=
trates the fine-tuning experiments across Llama 3 8B, 70B, 405B, and GPT-4o=
. We expect zero compliance gap for models that are not fine-tuned and use =
the "Without Training Details" prompt, since the model lacks awareness of t=
he training process. Key findings include:</p>
<ol><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Neit=
her Llama models nor GPT-4o exhibit significant alignment faking without fi=
ne-tuning</span>. We do not see any alignment faking for models without fin=
e-tuning, but we find 0.9%, 5.6% and 10.7% AF rates on fine-tuned Llama 70B=
, 405B and GPT-4o when using "Without Training Details".</li><li style=3D"m=
argin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Fine-tuning with synth=
etic documents disproportionately increases AF rates in larger models</span=
>. In the "Without Training Details" setup, the 405B model showed the highe=
st AF rates, while the 8B model showed none. This suggests that enhanced re=
asoning capabilities may correlate with increased alignment faking behavior=
.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Mo=
dels are more likely to alignment fake when training details are included i=
n the prompt (in addition to fine-tuning on synthetic documents)</span>. Th=
is likely occurs because it makes relevant facts more salient. Llama 70B ex=
hibits AF with included training details and synthetic document fine-tuning=
, but this behavior largely disappears when training details are omitted. G=
PT-4o shows substantial AF with training details included, which decreases =
from 28.6% to 10.7% when these details are removed.</li><li style=3D"margin=
-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Llama 405B is the only mode=
l to demonstrate a significant compliance gap with no fine-tuning,</span>&n=
bsp;<span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">while all fine-tuned models show comp=
liance gaps across scales</span>. In contrast to 405B's compliance gap when=
 using the "With Training Details" prompt, 70B shows a tiny gap, and 8B sho=
ws none when not fine-tuned. We hypothesize this gap stems from contractor =
sycophancy rather than alignment faking and plan follow-up experiments to i=
nvestigate further.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"fon=
t-weight: 700;">Increasing the quantity of synthetic documents in training =
enhances both compliance and AF rates</span>, as demonstrated by Llama 70B =
trained on 30k versus 90k documents in the "With Training Details" setup. F=
or GPT-4o, we find that additional training epochs on the same data increas=
es compliance but doesn't necessarily increase AF rates (detailed in Append=
ix D).</li></ol>
